title: For Sale:  Unserialized, unmarked, 80% AR-15 receivers, jig, end mills and drill bits (and I will buy the tools back after you're done).
postcontent:
Make your own, UNSERIALIZED legal AR-15 lower receiver. The ATF says that I can't loan you my tools-so I'll sell them to you instead. Here's how it works: $100 for the incomplete lower receiver, $125 for the steel jig to line everything up for you and $150 for the drill bits and end mills that you need to build it. Receiver can be used to build an AR pistol or a rifle. I sold all the receivers I had, sent in a new order and should have them in 4 days. Email me so we can make arrangements. 

Make your lower, don't break or abuse the bits or the jig and I will buy the bits and the jig back for $275. Or, if you want, keep them (your choice). This is an easy way to fabricate your own, legal, unmarked and unserialized lower receiver without creating a paper trail. 

Please note: this is only legal if a) you are not forbidden by law from owning or possessing a firearm; b) you are making the firearm for yourself and not to sell or give away; and c) if the firearm is in a legal configuration when complete (i.e., if you make an NFA item without NFA approval you can go to jail for a very long time). 

The jig and bits mean that all you need is a drill press. A milling machine is better, but drill press has worked for me just fine. No returns on the receiver (can't transfer it once it becomes a firearm and milling mistakes are your responsibility), but I will buy the jig and bits back as long as they are in good shape. 

Who knows how long it will be until the goons stop the sale of 80% receivers - and where else can you pay cash and avoid leaving a credit card trail? Don't miss out on the opportunity to exercise your right to keep and bear arms WITHOUT giving up your privacy.

title: For Sale:  Unserialized, unmarked, 80% AR-15 receivers, jig, end mills and drill bits (and I will buy the tools back after you're done).
postcontent:
Make your own, UNSERIALIZED legal AR-15 lower receiver. The ATF says that I can't loan you my tools-so I'll sell them to you instead. Here's how it works: $100 for the incomplete lower receiver, $125 for the steel jig to line everything up for you and $150 for the drill bits and end mills that you need to build it. Receiver can be used to build an AR pistol or a rifle. I sold all the receivers I had, sent in a new order and should have them in 4 days. Email me so we can make arrangements. 

Make your lower, don't break or abuse the bits or the jig and I will buy the bits and the jig back for $275. Or, if you want, keep them (your choice). This is an easy way to fabricate your own, legal, unmarked and unserialized lower receiver without creating a paper trail. 

Please note: this is only legal if a) you are not forbidden by law from owning or possessing a firearm; b) you are making the firearm for yourself and not to sell or give away; and c) if the firearm is in a legal configuration when complete (i.e., if you make an NFA item without NFA approval you can go to jail for a very long time). 

The jig and bits mean that all you need is a drill press. A milling machine is better, but drill press has worked for me just fine. No returns on the receiver (can't transfer it once it becomes a firearm and milling mistakes are your responsibility), but I will buy the jig and bits back as long as they are in good shape. 

Who knows how long it will be until the goons stop the sale of 80% receivers - and where else can you pay cash and avoid leaving a credit card trail? Don't miss out on the opportunity to exercise your right to keep and bear arms WITHOUT giving up your privacy.

The police 870s are considered the most reliable shotguns ever made and the ultimate home defense gun. This one has an 18" barrel and 4+1 capacity. Shoots 2 3/4" and 3" shells. I added a list below of the major differences between the police and express guns just to give you an idea of why they are more desirable HD guns. The 870 Police has:
- An aluminum trigger group (vs plastic on the 870 express).
- Old style magazine retention system (you can add mag extension w/o modification)  
- A much smoother finish inside and out, no machine marks or burrs.
- The Police gun receives a higher level of inspection and finishing and is built in a special area of the plant from 100% inspected parts.
- A military-grade parkerized finish.
- A polished bore.
- A one piece barrel.
- A short police-length fore end. 
- The Remington “R3” super recoil pad that reduces felt recoil by 30%.
- Sling swivels.
- Heavy-duty magazine spring to ensure positive shell feeding.
- Heavy-duty trigger-sear spring. to reduce the chance of accidental fire
- Heavy-duty shell lifter spring which also improves positive feeding.
- No use of MIM parts, the extractor is milled
- Police shotguns do not have an ISS (Integrated Safety System) which is a locking mechanism on the safety of commercial shotguns. This type of locking mechanism can cause delay to an officer who needs the weapon but does not have the appropriate key. LE shotguns have the standard, proven, cross bolt safety.
- The receivers used in Police guns are “vibra honed” to smooth out rough finishes and remove burrs before parkerization or bluing.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson Model 10-7 Double-action Revolver
location: Oregon Cash Company, INC, Medford, Oregon
postcontent:
This is a Smith & Wesson Model 10-7 Double-action Revolver chambered in the venerable and popular .38 Special cartridge.  The Smith & Wesson Model 10, previously known as the Smith & Wesson .38 Hand Ejector Model of 1899, the Smith & Wesson Military & Police, or the Smith & Wesson Victory Model, is a revolver of worldwide popularity. It was the successor to the Smith & Wesson .32 Hand Ejector Model of 1896 and was the first Smith & Wesson revolver to feature a cylinder release latch on the left side of the frame like the Colt M1889.  In production since 1899, it is a six-shot double-action revolver with fixed sights. Over its long production run it has been available with barrel lengths of 2 in (51 mm), 3 in (76 mm), 4 in (100 mm), 5 in (130 mm), and 6 in (150 mm). Barrels of 2.5 inches (64 mm) are also known to have been made for special contracts.  Some 6,000,000 of the type have been produced over the years, making it the most popular centerfire revolver of the 20th century.

The particular example, we are listing here, features the 4" barrel and will include the original blue box it was shipped from the factory in.  Additionally, the grips, [right grip panel], are numbered to the firearm with the serial number stamped into the inside surface of the panel.  No tools, oil paper, or documentation are included.

This firearm is rated as being in excellent condition with 99% of the bluing still on the metal.  There is a slight turn ring on the cylinder and the sharp edge of the muzzle shows some wear of the bluing.  There are a couple of minor nicks in the checkering of the grips, but other than this they are also in excellent condition.  The bore is also excellent.  As can be seen in the photos, the box has had tape placed around it sometime in the past.

Asking $549.95 Or best offer

title: For Sale:  SOLD   US M1917 Enfield Rifle, 30.06
location: Minneapolis Metro, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
This is the US Rifle Model 1917 that was adopted by the US Military in anticipation of our entry into WWI.  It's basically a British Pattern 1914 rifle that was being produced in the United States under British Contract that was re-chambered in the US Standard 30.06 Cartridge. 

At the time the M1903 Springfield was our official rifle, but production difficulties led to the adoption of the M1917 and more of the US Expeditionary Forces headed to Europe to fight in WWI were issued the M1917 than any other rifle.

This particular one was imported by Century International and was re-serialed on the left side of the receiver because the original markings were obliterated somehow and only faintly are partially visible.  The import bond inspection tag still is present on the trigger guard.

This would be a perfect one to use for a sporterized hunting rifle as the collectible nature of the rifle was seriously compromised with the re-serialed receiver.

Cal 30.06 with good bore.

REF #8643
